Below are the commands, grouped by the question each one answers. Set these first so the rest paste cleanly:

```bash
NS=portal              # your namespace
FE=portal-frontend     # frontend deployment name
BE=portal-backend      # backend deployment name
# discover real names if unsure:
kubectl get deploy,svc,ingress -n $NS
```

**1. Is this log even server-side? (settles the biggest fork for free)**

The single most informative check costs nothing. If your `Bearer undefined` and `has cookie true` lines appear in the *pod's* stdout, the interceptor is running on the Next.js **server** — browser `console.log` never reaches pod logs. That alone points at the "server can't read an HttpOnly/browser-held token" cause.

```bash
kubectl logs -n $NS deploy/$FE --tail=300 | grep -iE 'bearer|user/me|has cookie'
```

If those lines show up here → server-side execution confirmed. If they *only* appear in browser devtools and not here → it's client-side, and kubectl won't help much past step 2 (jump to the browser section).

**2. Does the frontend even have its auth config? (highest value, lowest effort)**

A missing `NEXTAUTH_SECRET`, wrong `NEXTAUTH_URL`, or absent Azure client config silently produces a session with no token attached.

```bash
kubectl exec -n $NS deploy/$FE -- env | grep -iE 'NEXT|AUTH|AZURE|OIDC|CLIENT|API|TENANT'
```

Look specifically for: `NEXTAUTH_URL` matching your real frontend URL, `NEXTAUTH_SECRET` present, and the API base resolving to `https://api.stg.portal.mycompany.com/api`.

**3. Is auth being terminated at the ALB? (the other big fork)**

If the ALB does OIDC, the token arrives as a header (`x-amzn-oidc-accesstoken`), not from any JS library — and SSR calls to the external URL get bounced to a login redirect.

```bash
kubectl describe ingress -n $NS | grep -iE 'auth|oidc'
# or full annotations:
kubectl get ingress -n $NS -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.name}{"\n"}{.metadata.annotations}{"\n\n"}{end}'
```

Presence of `alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/auth-type: oidc` (or `authenticate-oidc`) means your interceptor should read the OIDC header, not a cookie/store.

**4. Reproduce the call from inside the pod (exposes the SSR + external-URL trap)**

Your `BaseURL` is the *external* address. If SSR calls it, the request leaves the cluster, hits the ALB, and — with no browser cookies and possibly OIDC interception — comes back as a redirect or 401.

```bash
kubectl exec -n $NS deploy/$FE -- sh -c \
  'curl -sI https://api.stg.portal.mycompany.com/api/user/me'
```

A `302` to a login page → ALB OIDC is intercepting; SSR will never carry the token this way. A clean `401` → backend reached, just no/!valid token. Also test the in-cluster path to compare:

```bash
kubectl exec -n $NS deploy/$FE -- sh -c "curl -s -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\n' http://$BE:<port>/api/user/me"
```

**5. What does the backend actually receive?**

Confirms whether the literal string `Bearer undefined` even reaches it (vs the request dying earlier).

```bash
kubectl logs -n $NS deploy/$BE --tail=200 -f | grep -i 'user/me'
```

If you control the backend, temporarily log the incoming `Authorization` and `x-amzn-oidc-*` headers — that tells you definitively what's arriving.

**6. Are the manually-created secrets actually populated?**

You mentioned secrets are hand-created K8s Secrets — easy to have an empty or mis-keyed value.

```bash
kubectl get secret -n $NS
kubectl get secret <secret-name> -n $NS -o jsonpath='{.data}' | jq 'keys'   # keys only
# confirm a value is non-empty without dumping it:
kubectl get secret <secret-name> -n $NS -o jsonpath='{.data.NEXTAUTH_SECRET}' | base64 -d | wc -c
```

**Browser side (for the client-side branch — kubectl can't see this):**

If step 1 showed the logs are *not* in the pod, the truth is in devtools: Network tab → the `/user/me` request → Request Headers (what `Authorization` actually got sent), and Application → Cookies (whether the session cookie is flagged `HttpOnly` — if so, `document.cookie` can't read it, which is your bug).

Run 1, 2, and 3 first — those three usually tell you which of the four causes you're in. Paste back the output of step 1 (server vs client) and step 3 (any OIDC annotations) and I can tell you the exact fix rather than the family.